ce:section.ce:para:
The fluorescence detection sensitivity of Nb2C QDs toward Fe3+ was further studied through spectrophotometric titration experiment. Fig. 5d shows a gradual fluorescence emission decrease of Nb2C QDs with the increasing concentration of Fe3+, implying the feasibility of Nb2C QDs for Fe3+ detection. As the concentration of Fe3+ varies from 0 to 300 μM (Fig. 5e), the fluorescence intensity ratio between Nb2C QDs and Nb2C QDs-Fe3+ complex (F0/F) displays a good linear correlation as increasing Fe3+. According to the Stern–Volmer equation, F/F0 = 1 + Ksv
                        Q, the quenching constant (Ksv
                        ) is determined to be 1.81 × 103 L mol−1 [10]. Therefore, the detection limit as low as 0.89 μM is expected at a signal-to-noise ratio of 3. For comparison, some representative nanofluorophore platforms for sensing Fe3+ are summarized in Table S1. It can be seen from Table S1 that the Nb2C QDs exhibit better or comparable performance, including a wide linear range and low detection limit. These results indicate that Nb2C QDs are promising fluorescent probes for Fe3+ sensing with high selectivity and sensitivity.
